  "prompt": "Why do Pharaohs cross their arms?",
  "response": "Pharaohs are often depicted with their arms crossed as a symbol of royalty and power. This pose, known as the \"Osiride\" pose, is named after the Egyptian god Osiris, who was typically shown in this manner. The crossed arms are meant to hold the crook and flail, which were important symbols of kingship and authority in ancient Egyptian culture. The crook represented the Pharaoh's role as a shepherd of his people, while the flail symbolized the monarch's ability to provide for and protect his subjects. The crossed arms pose was used in various forms of art, including statues and reliefs, to emphasize the Pharaoh's divine status and connection to the gods.",
